Banco Michacha is a new cooperative located in southern Ethiopia in the Kercha District of the Guji Zone.  Its  members are smallholder farmers meaning that their farms are very modest and typically operated by the members of the family with no outside hired help.
At the end of each day's harvest, the farmers bring their perfectly ripe coffee cherries to the receiving station of the Banco Michicha wet mill.  Their delivery is weighed and they are paid cash for the day’s pick.  Since it is a farmer-owned cooperative under the Oromia Coffee Farmers Cooperative Union, the prices and policies are set by farmers.
The coffee cherries are depulped using a disk depulping machine.  The outer fruit is discarded and composted.  The mucilage-covered seeds are then deposited in a tile-lined tank and fermented for - hours underwater.  Finally the seeds are washed in tile-lined canals before heading to their last  hour soak in clean water.  
 As a whole, Ethiopia has excellent conditions for drying coffee.  This coffee was dried out in the open air using raised beds for approximately  days.  These beds provide excellent airflow for even drying at the perfect rate.  The result is a vibrant coffee that roasts evenly and holds on to its quality for a much longer time than coffees from other growing regions.  
The member farms of Banco Michicha sit between  and  meters above sea level and grow Ethiopian heirloom varieties.
